paragraph.content: University of Massachusetts Heart and Vascular Center of Excellence
Heart and Vascular Invasive Laboratory Vascular Procedure Report

Oscar Williams is a 63 y.o. male who presents for angiography and possible endovascular intervention for difficulty with cannulation and use of his right brachiocephalic fistula. Of note, patient has a right-sided pacemaker as well as a left tunneled dialysis catheter
Fistulagram with possible Intervention and possible use of Moderate Sedation
Access: Ultrasound-guided access of arteriovenous fistula
Procedures: Fistulagram of peripheral and central venous system
Angioplasty of Innominate vein and Superior vena cava
Statement of Attending Surgeon's Presence: The attending surgeon, Sally, MD, was present during the entire procedure.
HV Nurse: Ashley E Piader, RN
HV X-Ray Technologist: Tiffany A Culberson, RT(R)
HV Documenter: Tracy A Padgett, RN

Pre-sedation history and evaluation revealed no contraindications to moderate sedation. The patient received lidocaine, benzodiazepines and/or opioids, the dosing of which is documented in the patient's permanent medical record. The procedural nursing staff and Sally, MD monitored the patient's level of consciousness and physiologic status continuously throughout the procedure. Total intra-service moderate sedation time was 0 Hr 37 Min 0 Sec minutes.
ASA: ASA status not filed in the log.
Estimated Blood Loss: No blood loss documented.

Fistulagram of brachiocephalic demonstrated widely patent fistula with high-grade stenosis in the SVC and right innominate in the setting of previously placed pacer wires as well as a left IJ tunnel catheter

The patient was placed in a supine position on the angiography table. Physiologic monitoring was initiated. Moderate sedation for patient comfort and analgesia was provided at the direction and constant supervision of the attending surgeon. The extremity was prepped and draped utilizing CHG. A time out was called. With ultrasound guidance, the brachiocephalic fistula was accessed with Micropuncture system and an image was saved. A guidewire was advanced and a 6 French sheath placed over the wire. Angiography was performed with findings as noted above.

Utilizing a Glidewire and glide catheter, we were successfully able to traverse through the pacer wires and IJ tunnel catheter to place our Glidewire in the IVC. We then proceeded with balloon angioplasty with a 10 mm followed by 12 mm balloon through the SVC and innominate. This revealed now widely patent drainage through the central veins. Retrograde imaging also showed a widely patent we elected to end at this time.
At the end of the procedure hemostasis was obtained with pursestring suture. A sterile dressing was applied. The patient was transferred to the recovery area in satisfactory condition.
Fistulagram with findings as described above.
High-grade stenosis of the central venous system which was balloon angioplastied with good result
Post Procedure Plan/Follow up: They can attempt to use the fistula immediately with plan for hopeful removal of his left IJ tunnel catheter
